        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Nursery &amp; Seed Establishment, | Westerham</placeName>
                    <date>Aug 13<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>— 1855</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
<p>In answer to your enquiries respecting the German Seeds<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I beg to say I import my own direct and I find the quality so superior to what I used to get from the wholesale dealers in London that every year I find a very great increase in the demand. The best quality I have ever got has been from Mess<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. C. Platz &amp; Son, Erfurt, Prussia Frederick Adolphus Haage Jun<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. also of Erfurt is a good grower of them and also Charles Appelius of the same place. G. H. Behn of Hamburgh also grows them good and extensively.</p>
<p>I am | Sir | Your most obed<hi rend="superscript">t</hi> Sert— | John Cattell <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/> C. Darwin Esqr</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Cattell’s catalogue of floricultural seeds advertised German seeds. CD’s copy of the 1855 catalogue is heavily marked for those he intended to order (DAR 46.2: 2). See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1741.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. D. Hooker, 14 [August 1855]</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
